---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import SiteNav from "../components/SiteNav.astro";
import SiteFooter from "../components/SiteFooter.astro";
import "../styles/manual.css";
import "../styles/force-glyphs.css";

// A second, playful homepage — "field-ui, explained like you're 5". Same engine and the same
// home structure (the shared <field-root>, the chapter/stage layout, and the HomeRuntime +
// StageFieldOverlay wiring at the bottom), but a story-first narrative instead of the manual.
//
// Every stage here is a REAL body in the shared field — the demos use the same data-* contract
// as the main home page (data-body / data-drag / data-feedback / data-threads / data-preset), so
// nothing is faked: the dots actually swim, and the field-line overlay traces the true paths.
// The runtime only activates on pages with `.manual-shell`, which this page provides.
---

<Base
  title="field-ui — explained like you're 5"
  description="A webpage you can play with, that plays back. field-ui sprinkles invisible magnets onto a page: a word can call the dots in, a button can push them away, and when matter piles up the word notices and grows. Things bend the field; the field bends them back — and the dots are just the easiest thing to see."
>
  <SiteNav />
  <div class="manual-shell">
    <header class="manual-hero" id="top">
      <div class="wrap">
        <p class="kicker">field-ui · explained like you're 5</p>
        <h1>Web elements have <span class="accent">mass</span>.</h1>
        <p class="standfirst">
          Not literally — but it sure starts to feel that way. field-ui sprinkles
          invisible magnets onto a webpage: a word can say “come here!” and the
          little floating dots all swim toward it. A button can say “stay back!”
          and they scoot away. Some things spin the dots in circles; some gobble
          them up like a tiny black hole.
        </p>
        <p class="thesis">
          <strong>And the magic part — it goes both ways.</strong> Pile enough dots
          on a word and the word notices: it grows bigger, bolder, glowier. Things
          bend the invisible field, and the field bends them back.
        </p>
        <div class="hero-cta">
          <a class="btn primary" href="/docs">Read the docs →</a>
          <a class="btn" href="/lab">Open the Lab →</a>
          <a class="btn" href="/">See the grown-up version →</a>
        </div>
        <div class="hero-flow">
          <button
            id="flowToggle"
            class="flow-toggle"
            type="button"
            aria-pressed="false"
          >
            <span class="ft-dot" aria-hidden="true"></span>Make the dots follow you
          </button>
          <span class="flow-hint"
            >move your cursor — the whole field leans toward it</span
          >
        </div>
      </div>
    </header>

    <nav class="chapter-rail" aria-label="Chapters">
      <a href="#ch-magnets" data-ch="ch-magnets"
        ><span class="cr-no">1</span><span class="cr-label">Magnets</span></a
      >
      <a href="#ch-things" data-ch="ch-things"
        ><span class="cr-no">2</span><span class="cr-label">Not just dots</span
        ></a
      >
      <a href="#ch-physics" data-ch="ch-physics"
        ><span class="cr-no">3</span><span class="cr-label">Real physics</span></a
      >
      <a href="#ch-recipes" data-ch="ch-recipes"
        ><span class="cr-no">4</span><span class="cr-label">Recipes</span></a
      >
      <a href="#ch-together" data-ch="ch-together"
        ><span class="cr-no">5</span><span class="cr-label">Together</span></a
      >
      <a href="#ch-toybox" data-ch="ch-toybox"
        ><span class="cr-no">6</span><span class="cr-label">Toy box</span></a
      >
      <a href="#ch-honest" data-ch="ch-honest"
        ><span class="cr-no">7</span><span class="cr-label">Honest truth</span></a
      >
    </nav>

    <!-- 1 · The invisible magnets -->
    <div class="chapter" id="ch-magnets">
      <div class="wrap">
        <span class="chapter-no">1</span>
        <h2 class="chapter-title">The invisible magnets</h2>
        <p class="chapter-sub">
          Drop a magnet on the page and watch the little dots react. Drag any of
          them around — the pull or push follows the word, not your cursor.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="concept reverse" data-form="wells">
      <div class="wrap concept-grid">
        <div>
          <span class="concept-no"
            ><i class="fg fg-attract" style="--fc:#4da3ff"></i>Come here!</span
          >
          <h2>A word can call the dots in.</h2>
          <p>
            An <strong>attractor</strong> says “come here!” and the floating dots
            all swim toward it. The pull is tied to the word — drag it across the
            field and the dots chase it.
          </p>
          <p class="note">Give it a poke and watch the dots rush back in.</p>
          <button class="agitate" data-agitate="#m-attract">↯ Poke the field</button
          >
        </div>
        <div class="stage">
          <span class="stage-label">come here — drag me</span>
          <span
            class="body-chip"
            id="m-attract"
            data-drag
            data-body="attract"
            data-strength="1"
            data-range="300"
            style="--cc:#4da3ff; position:absolute; left:50%; top:50%; transform:translate(-50%,-50%);"
            ><i class="fg fg-attract"></i>come here</span
          >
          <span class="hintline">the dots swim toward it</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="concept" data-form="scatter">
      <div class="wrap concept-grid">
        <div>
          <span class="concept-no"
            ><i class="fg fg-repel" style="--fc:#ff9d5c"></i>Stay back!</span
          >
          <h2>Or push them all away.</h2>
          <p>
            A <strong>repeller</strong> says “stay back!” — it carves out a clean
            space and the dots flow around it instead of through it.
          </p>
          <p class="note">Drag it into the crowd and watch a clearing open.</p>
          <button class="agitate" data-agitate="#m-repel">↯ Poke the field</button>
        </div>
        <div class="stage">
          <span class="stage-label">stay back — drag me</span>
          <span
            class="body-chip"
            id="m-repel"
            data-drag
            data-body="repel"
            data-strength="1.1"
            data-range="300"
            style="--cc:#ff9d5c; position:absolute; left:50%; top:50%; transform:translate(-50%,-50%);"
            ><i class="fg fg-repel"></i>stay back</span
          >
          <span class="hintline">a clearing opens around it</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="concept reverse" data-form="wells">
      <div class="wrap concept-grid">
        <div>
          <span class="concept-no"
            ><i class="fg fg-swirl" style="--fc:#2dd4bf"></i>Spin them</span
          >
          <h2>Some things spin the dots in circles.</h2>
          <p>
            A <strong>swirl</strong> sends the dots wheeling around it like water
            going down a drain — but gently, so they orbit instead of falling in.
          </p>
          <p class="note">Drag it through the swarm and stir.</p>
          <button class="agitate" data-agitate="#m-swirl">↯ Poke the field</button>
        </div>
        <div class="stage">
          <span class="stage-label">spin — drag me</span>
          <span
            class="body-chip"
            id="m-swirl"
            data-drag
            data-body="swirl"
            data-spin="1"
            data-strength="1"
            data-range="320"
            style="--cc:#2dd4bf; position:absolute; left:50%; top:50%; transform:translate(-50%,-50%);"
            ><i class="fg fg-swirl"></i>spin</span
          >
          <span class="hintline">the dots wheel around, never collapse</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="concept" data-form="accretion">
      <div class="wrap concept-grid">
        <div>
          <span class="concept-no"
            ><i class="fg fg-sink" style="--fc:#ff6e9c"></i>Gobble them</span
          >
          <h2>Some gobble them up like a tiny black hole.</h2>
          <p>
            A <strong>sink</strong> swallows the dots that wander too close —
            holding them at its core, not deleting them. Nothing is conjured from
            nothing; matter just changes hands.
          </p>
          <p class="note">Poke the field and feed it.</p>
          <button class="agitate" data-agitate="#m-sink">↯ Feed it</button>
        </div>
        <div class="stage">
          <span class="stage-label">gobble — drag me</span>
          <span
            class="body-chip"
            id="m-sink"
            data-drag
            data-body="sink attract"
            data-absorb="64"
            data-max="14"
            data-strength="0.9"
            data-range="240"
            style="--cc:#ff6e9c; position:absolute; left:50%; top:50%; transform:translate(-50%,-50%);"
            ><i class="fg fg-sink"></i>gobble</span
          >
          <span class="hintline">dots get held at the core</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="concept reverse">
      <div class="wrap concept-grid">
        <div>
          <span class="concept-no">✨ Both ways</span>
          <h2>And here’s the magic — it goes both ways.</h2>
          <p>
            The word pulls the dots in… and when lots of dots pile up, the word
            <strong>notices</strong>. It gets heavier, bolder, and glowier. The
            dots push the word, the word pushes back — they play together,
            forever. That’s the whole idea.
          </p>
          <p class="note">Hover the word — pull the dots in and watch it grow.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="stage">
          <span class="stage-label">pile up → it grows</span>
          <span
            class="live-demo"
            data-hot
            data-color="#a78bfa"
            data-feedback
            data-body="attract"
            data-strength="1"
            data-range="300"
            style="--cat:#a78bfa;">notice me</span
          >
          <span class="hintline">gathered dots make the word heavier</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 2 · When it's not just dots -->
    <div class="chapter" id="ch-things">
      <div class="wrap">
        <span class="chapter-no">2</span>
        <h2 class="chapter-title">When it’s not just dots</h2>
        <p class="chapter-sub">
          Here’s the secret: the dots were never the point. The field doesn’t care
          what you drop into it — the real words, the lines between them, even
          where you’re looking can all play.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="concept" data-form="wells">
      <div class="wrap concept-grid">
        <div>
          <span class="concept-no">🅰️ Living type</span>
          <h2>The word itself gains weight — literally.</h2>
          <p>
            This is the “mass” from the title, made real. The word is a magnet: it
            pulls the dots in, they pool beneath it, and that pile drives its
            <em>whole look at once</em> — <strong>weight, size, spacing, glow, even
            colour</strong>. One number does all of it. Scatter the pile and the
            type goes light and pale, then thickens back as the field re-gathers
            under its own pull. Type as a <strong>material</strong>, not a style.
          </p>
          <p class="note">
            Hit the button — scatter the pile, watch the letters thin out and pale,
            then fatten back up.
          </p>
          <button class="agitate" data-agitate="#mat-word">↯ Disturb the type</button>
        </div>
        <div class="stage">
          <span class="stage-label">one number → every type axis</span>
          <span
            class="material-word"
            id="mat-word"
            data-hot
            data-feedback
            data-body="attract"
            data-strength="1.2"
            data-range="300"
            data-color="#f0abfc"
            style="--cc:#f0abfc; --cat:#f0abfc;">mass</span
          >
          <span class="hintline">weight, size, spacing, glow and colour are one density</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="concept reverse">
      <div class="wrap concept-grid">
        <div>
          <span class="concept-no">🔗 Lines between things</span>
          <h2>Related things tie themselves together.</h2>
          <p>
            A footnote and the sentence it belongs to are joined by an invisible
            rubber band — tug one and the other tugs back. Related things pull
            together; things that argue push apart. The connections become real,
            physical, grabbable.
          </p>
          <p class="note">Hover any word to light up its set.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="stage">
          <span class="stage-label">a connected set</span>
          <div class="thread-set" data-index data-threads>
            <span
              class="ti"
              data-hot
              data-color="#4da3ff"
              data-body="attract"
              data-strength="0.5"
              data-range="220"
              style="--cat:#4da3ff;">claim</span
            >
            <span
              class="ti"
              data-hot
              data-color="#2dd4bf"
              data-body="attract"
              data-strength="0.5"
              data-range="220"
              style="--cat:#2dd4bf;">proof</span
            >
            <span
              class="ti"
              data-hot
              data-color="#a78bfa"
              data-body="attract"
              data-strength="0.5"
              data-range="220"
              style="--cat:#a78bfa;">source</span
            >
            <span
              class="ti"
              data-hot
              data-color="#ff9d5c"
              data-body="attract"
              data-strength="0.5"
              data-range="220"
              style="--cat:#ff9d5c;">footnote</span
            >
          </div>
          <span class="hintline">threads connect what belongs together</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="concept" data-attention-demo>
      <div class="wrap concept-grid">
        <div>
          <span class="concept-no">👀 Where you’re looking</span>
          <h2>The page knows you’re here.</h2>
          <p>
            As you scroll, the part you’re reading lights up like a flashlight
            beam — and the page remembers where you’ve already been, so those
            spots stay a little warm, like footprints in sand. A long article
            suddenly knows “you are here, you’ve read this.”
          </p>
          <p class="note">
            There’s only one spotlight of focus — hover one word and the others
            politely dim. Nothing screams for attention all at once.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="stage">
          <span class="stage-label">one spotlight, shared</span>
          <div class="attn-set">
            <span
              class="attn-word"
              data-hot
              data-feedback
              data-body="attract"
              data-strength="1.5"
              data-range="240"
              data-color="#4da3ff"
              style="--cat:#4da3ff;">here</span
            >
            <span
              class="attn-word"
              data-hot
              data-feedback
              data-body="attract"
              data-strength="1.5"
              data-range="240"
              data-color="#2dd4bf"
              style="--cat:#2dd4bf;">now</span
            >
            <span
              class="attn-word"
              data-hot
              data-feedback
              data-body="attract"
              data-strength="1.5"
              data-range="240"
              data-color="#ff9d5c"
              style="--cat:#ff9d5c;">read</span
            >
          </div>
          <span class="hintline">engage one — the others give up their glow</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="concept reverse" data-causality-demo>
      <div class="wrap concept-grid">
        <div>
          <span class="concept-no">💡 It spills over</span>
          <h2>Light up one — its neighbours catch.</h2>
          <p>
            When one thing gets crowded with dots, the extra <strong>spills to
            whoever’s nearby</strong> — more to the close ones, less to the far
            ones, and never more than there was to begin with. So lighting up one
            tile lights its neighbours <em>on their own</em>. The glow flows between
            things because the matter actually does.
          </p>
          <p class="note">
            Hover the middle tile — the ones beside it catch, and the far ones
            flicker faintly.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="stage">
          <span class="stage-label">spill → neighbours light</span>
          <div class="causal-set">
            <span class="causal-node" data-hot data-feedback data-body="attract" data-strength="1.4" data-range="200" data-color="#a78bfa" style="--cat:#a78bfa;"></span>
            <span class="causal-node" data-hot data-feedback data-body="attract" data-strength="1.4" data-range="200" data-color="#7dd3fc" style="--cat:#7dd3fc;"></span>
            <span class="causal-node" data-hot data-feedback data-body="attract" data-strength="1.4" data-range="200" data-color="#4da3ff" style="--cat:#4da3ff;"></span>
            <span class="causal-node" data-hot data-feedback data-body="attract" data-strength="1.4" data-range="200" data-color="#2dd4bf" style="--cat:#2dd4bf;"></span>
            <span class="causal-node" data-hot data-feedback data-body="attract" data-strength="1.4" data-range="200" data-color="#86e57f" style="--cat:#86e57f;"></span>
          </div>
          <span class="hintline">engage one — the extra spills to whoever’s near</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="concept big-idea">
      <div class="wrap">
        <p class="bigidea-kicker">The big idea</p>
        <h2>
          Dots show you the field is there. <span class="accent"
            >Everything else is what the field is for.</span
          >
        </h2>
        <p>
          It’s not “a webpage with floating dots.” It’s a webpage where meaning has
          weight — where being important, being related, being trusted, or being
          already-read are things you can <strong>see and feel</strong>, not just
          words someone typed.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 3 · It's borrowing real physics -->
    <div class="chapter" id="ch-physics">
      <div class="wrap">
        <span class="chapter-no">3</span>
        <h2 class="chapter-title">It’s borrowing real physics</h2>
        <p class="chapter-sub">
          Some of these magnets aren’t pretend at all — they run the actual laws of
          the universe. And the team is careful to always say which is which.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="concept reverse" data-form="wells">
      <div class="wrap concept-grid">
        <div>
          <span class="concept-no"
            ><i class="fg fg-attract" style="--fc:#86e57f"></i>Real gravity</span
          >
          <h2>Closer means a <em>lot</em> stronger.</h2>
          <p>
            This one isn’t a tuned-up UI effect — it’s real <strong>gravity</strong>,
            the same softened inverse-square law the planets use. Drag it near the
            swarm and the pull ramps up fast; back it away and it fades to almost
            nothing.
          </p>
          <p class="note">Drag it close, then far — feel the falloff change.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="stage">
          <span class="stage-label">real gravity — drag me</span>
          <span
            class="body-chip"
            id="m-gravity"
            data-drag
            data-body="gravity"
            data-strength="1"
            data-range="340"
            style="--cc:#86e57f; position:absolute; left:50%; top:50%; transform:translate(-50%,-50%);"
            ><i class="fg fg-attract"></i>gravity</span
          >
          <span class="hintline">close = a hard pull; far = barely a whisper</span>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="concept">
      <div class="wrap">
        <span class="concept-no">🌍 Four forces, four feelings</span>
        <h2>
          The universe has four big forces. field-ui borrows all four — as
          <span class="accent">feelings</span>.
        </h2>
        <ul class="fourfields">
          <li>
            <span class="ff-real">Gravity</span><span class="ff-arrow">→</span>
            <strong>importance</strong>
            <span class="ff-say">things gather around what matters</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ff-real">Electricity</span><span class="ff-arrow">→</span>
            <strong>agree or argue</strong>
            <span class="ff-say">opposites attract, sames push apart</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ff-real">The glue force</span><span class="ff-arrow">→</span>
            <strong>belonging</strong>
            <span class="ff-say">things that go together stick together</span>
          </li>
          <li>
            <span class="ff-real">The decay force</span><span class="ff-arrow">→</span>
            <strong>fading</strong>
            <span class="ff-say">old things let go and drift away</span>
          </li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          So when something feels <em>important</em>, it’s literally using gravity.
          When two facts <em>disagree</em>, that’s electricity pushing them apart.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="concept reverse">
      <div class="wrap">
        <span class="concept-no">🧪 Real, tuned, or pretend?</span>
        <h2>And it always tells you which is which.</h2>
        <div class="buckets">
          <div class="bucket">
            <span class="bk-emoji" aria-hidden="true">🧪</span>
            <h3>Real physics</h3>
            <p>
              The genuine laws — <code>gravity</code>, <code>charge</code>,
              <code>magnetism</code>, heat, waves, bouncing.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bucket">
            <span class="bk-emoji" aria-hidden="true">🎨</span>
            <h3>Tuned to feel nice</h3>
            <p>
              The everyday <code>attract</code>, <code>repel</code>,
              <code>swirl</code> — softened so a page stays calm and readable.
            </p>
          </div>
          <div class="bucket">
            <span class="bk-emoji" aria-hidden="true">🌌</span>
            <h3>Pure pretend</h3>
            <p>
              Real pieces stacked into make-believe — <code>blackhole</code>,
              <code>galaxy</code>, <code>tornado</code>.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p class="note">
          The trap they warn about: <code>attract</code> is <strong>not</strong>
          gravity. One is the universe’s rule; the other just borrows its costume.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- 4 · The cookbook -->
    <div class="chapter" id="ch-recipes">
      <div class="wrap">
        <span class="chapter-no">4</span>
        <h2 class="chapter-title">The cookbook</h2>
        <p class="chapter-sub">
          You rarely build with raw magnets. You build with <strong>recipes</strong>
          — little cards, exactly like a recipe for cookies, except it’s magnets +
          how it looks + what it means.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <section class="concept">
      <div class="wrap concept-grid">
        <div>
          <span class="concept-no">📇 A recipe is a card</span>
          <h2>Magnets, a look, and a meaning — on one card.</h2>
          <p>
            Every card keeps its boxes separate: <em>idea words</em> describe,
            <strong>magnet names</strong> do the work, <em>measurements</em> just
            count. You can be poetic in the idea box, but the magnet box has to name
            a <strong>real</strong> magnet — and a checker bounces any card that
            fibs. There are already 64 of them.
          </p>
          <p class="note">A new idea is usually just a new card — no new physics.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="recipe-col">
          <div class="recipe-card">
            <span class="rc-name">Evidence Field</span>
            <span class="rc-for">for showing whether you can trust an answer</span>
            <dl>
              <dt>Magnets</dt>
              <dd><code>charge</code> <code>link</code> <code>repel</code> <code>memory</code></dd>
              <dt>Wire</dt>
              <dd>each claim → its sources</dd>
              <dt>Draw</dt>
              <dd>dots · threads · a soft glow</dd>
              <dt>Motion off</dt>
              <dd>a plain list with ✓ and ✗</dd>
            </dl>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="concept reverse" data-form="ambient">
      <div class="wrap concept-grid">
        <div>
          <span class="concept-no">🌊 One pond</span>
          <h2>Drop in two recipes and they share the same water.</h2>
          <p>
            Here’s the secret: there’s only <strong>one pond</strong>. Every magnet
            on the page tugs the <em>same</em> dots, so the pulls just add up — like
            two kids pulling one wagon. A page isn’t a <em>list</em> of separate
            effects; it’s a <strong>soup</strong>, where everything ripples through
            everything else.
          </p>
          <p class="note">Drag both — watch them fight over the same dots.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="stage">
          <span class="stage-label">two magnets, one pond — drag both</span>
